Statements: however, il-2 activates multiple intracellular pathways in addition to stat5-mediated signaling, including mitogen-activated protein kinase (mapk) and pi3k–akt–mtor pathways (boyman and sprent, 2012; liao et al., 2013). surprisingly, despite their increased phosphorylation of stat5, itk-deficient cells showed less il-2–induced phosphorylation of s6, suggesting reduced mtor activation compared with wt cells (fig. 6 c). similar results were observed when cells were initially stimulated under itreg cell conditions with low concentrations of anti-cd3, so that wt and itk-deficient cells had equivalent percentages of foxp3+ cells (not depicted). these results suggest that itk deficiency did not simply increase il-2 responses, but rather altered signaling in response to il-2, such that stat5 activation was uncoupled from mtor activation.
